<?php
$distributionOptions = array("a" => "Population distribution", "b" => "Sample distribution", "c" => "Sampling distribution");
return array(
    "overview" => "A sampling distribution does not graph raw student values from one sample. It graphs a statistic from each of many equal-sized random samples. This repeated-sampling idea explains bias, precision, standard error, and every formula that follows.",
    "objectives" => array("Distinguish population, sample, and sampling distributions.", "Describe repeated sampling and sampling variability.", "Explain what makes an estimator unbiased.", "Connect sample size with estimator variability and precision.", "Interpret a sampling simulation without confusing dots, individuals, and statistics."),
    "prerequisites" => array("Distinguish population parameters from sample statistics.", "Identify random samples and bias.", "Interpret the centre, spread, and shape of a distribution."),
    "vocabulary" => array(
        array("Population distribution", "The distribution of variable values for every individual in the population."), array("Sample distribution", "The distribution of individual values in one selected sample."),
        array("Sampling distribution", "The probability distribution of a statistic across all possible random samples of a fixed size."), array("Repeated sampling", "Selecting many samples by the same random method and calculating the same statistic each time."),
        array("Sampling variability", "Natural change in a statistic from sample to sample."), array("Estimator", "A statistic used to estimate a population parameter."),
        array("Unbiased estimator", "An estimator whose sampling-distribution centre equals the target parameter."), array("Precision", "How tightly an estimator's sampling distribution clusters."),
        array("Simulation", "A repeated random model used to approximate long-run behaviour."), array("Sample size", "The number of individuals in each sample, written \\(n\\).")
    ),
    "sections" => array(
        array("title" => "One Population, Many Possible Samples", "content" => array(
            "<p>Suppose a school contains 2,400 homework times. That complete set has a population distribution with its own shape, centre, and spread. A random sample of 40 students produces a sample distribution containing 40 individual homework times. A second sample of 40 contains different students and therefore different values.</p>",
            "<p>From each sample, calculate one statistic, such as the mean. Repeating the process many times produces means such as 46.1, 43.7, 47.4, 44.8, and 45.5 minutes. The distribution of those means is a <strong>sampling distribution</strong>. Each dot is one sample mean, not one student's homework time.</p>",
            "<p>Formally, a sampling distribution describes a statistic over all possible random samples of the same size from the same population. A simulation using hundreds or thousands of samples approximates that theoretical distribution.</p>",
            array("type" => "definition", "label" => "The one-dot question", "html" => "<p>Ask what one plotted value represents. One individual value suggests a population or sample distribution. One statistic calculated from an entire sample suggests a sampling distribution.</p>")
        ), "simulation" => "sampling"),
        array("title" => "The Three Distributions", "content" => array(
            "<p>The <strong>population distribution</strong> answers: how does the variable vary among all individuals? Its observations might be all users' weekly assignment counts. The <strong>sample distribution</strong> answers the same type of individual-level question for one sample only. It is used to learn about the population but may not match it exactly.</p>",
            "<p>The <strong>sampling distribution</strong> answers a different question: how would a statistic vary if sampling were repeated? Its values could be sample means, sample proportions, medians, or differences between groups. It is a distribution of estimates.</p>",
            "<table><thead><tr><th>Distribution</th><th>What one value represents</th><th>Typical size</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Population</td><td>One individual's measurement</td><td>Population size \\(N\\)</td></tr><tr><td>Sample</td><td>One sampled individual's measurement</td><td>Sample size \\(n\\)</td></tr><tr><td>Sampling</td><td>One statistic from one sample</td><td>Number of possible or simulated samples</td></tr></tbody></table>",
            "<p>A histogram labelled \"sample means\" is not the histogram of one sample. The plural refers to many means, each of which summarizes a whole sample.</p>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Sampling Variability Is Expected", "content" => array(
            "<p>Random samples contain different individuals, so their statistics differ. This <strong>sampling variability</strong> is not automatically a mistake or bias. If the true population mean is 45 minutes, a random sample mean of 44.2 can still be a reasonable estimate.</p>",
            "<p>A sampling distribution makes variability measurable. Its centre shows the typical estimate, its spread shows how much estimates change, and its shape shows which values are common or rare. Later lessons calculate that spread as standard error and use the shape to find probabilities.</p>",
            "<p>Increasing sample size usually reduces sampling variability because each statistic averages information from more individuals. It does not change the population values or parameter. It changes how stable the estimator is from one random sample to another.</p>",
            array("type" => "warning", "label" => "Variation versus bias", "html" => "<p>Variation spreads estimates around their centre. Bias shifts the centre away from the target. An estimator can have low variability and high bias, or low bias and high variability.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Bias and Precision of an Estimator", "content" => array(
            "<p>An estimator is <strong>unbiased</strong> when the mean of its sampling distribution equals the population parameter. Under random sampling, the sample mean \\(\\bar{x}\\) is unbiased for the population mean \\(\\mu\\), and the sample proportion \\(\\hat p\\) is unbiased for the population proportion \\(p\\).</p>",
            "<p>Unbiased does not mean every estimate is exactly correct. Some sample means fall above and others below the population mean. Their long-run balance centres at the parameter. A particular random sample can still be far away.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Precision</strong> concerns spread. A narrow sampling distribution gives more stable estimates. Larger random samples generally improve precision. However, a large convenience sample may be tightly centred on the wrong value. Precision cannot compensate for systematic bias.</p>",
            array("type" => "example", "label" => "Target analogy", "html" => "<p>Bias describes whether shots centre on the bullseye. Variability describes whether they cluster tightly. A tight cluster off-centre is precise but biased.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Read a Sampling Simulation", "content" => array(
            "<p>A simulation begins with a fixed population. Choose a sample size \\(n\\), draw a random sample, calculate one statistic, place it on a graph, and repeat. Early dots look irregular. After hundreds of repetitions, the distribution's centre, spread, and shape become easier to see.</p>",
            "<p>Change only one setting at a time. Comparing \\(n=5\\) with \\(n=50\\) from the same population isolates sample-size effects. The centres should remain near the same parameter, while the larger-sample statistics cluster more tightly.</p>",
            "<p>Simulation does not change the true population and does not prove that one observed sample is representative. It demonstrates long-run behaviour under the specified model. A biased selection rule simulated thousands of times would faithfully reveal the behaviour of that biased rule.</p>"
        ))
    ),
    "worked_examples" => array(
        array("title" => "Name the distribution", "scenario" => "A graph contains the homework times of 40 randomly selected students.", "steps" => array("Each graph value is one student's time.", "The 40 values come from one selected group.", "No repeated sample statistics are shown."), "conclusion" => "This is a sample distribution."),
        array("title" => "Means from 1,000 samples", "scenario" => "A graph contains 1,000 means, each calculated from a random sample of 40 students.", "steps" => array("Each graph value summarizes an entire sample.", "The same statistic and sample size are used repeatedly.", "The graph describes sample-to-sample behaviour."), "conclusion" => "This is a sampling distribution of the sample mean."),
        array("title" => "Compare n=10 and n=100", "scenario" => "Both sampling distributions estimate the same population proportion using random samples.", "steps" => array("Both centres should equal the same population proportion because sample proportion is unbiased.", "The n=100 distribution should be narrower because larger samples vary less.", "The population parameter remains unchanged."), "conclusion" => "The larger sample improves precision, not the target parameter."),
    ),
    "misconceptions" => array(
        array("A sampling distribution graphs raw sample data.", "It graphs one statistic from each of many samples."), array("One sample creates the full sampling distribution.", "A single sample contributes one statistic, one dot."),
        array("Every random sample has the same statistic.", "Sampling variability is expected."), array("Sampling variability means bias.", "Random spread can be centred correctly."),
        array("A statistic must equal the parameter to be useful.", "An unbiased estimator is correct on average, not in every sample."), array("A larger sample changes the parameter.", "It changes estimator spread, not the fixed population value.")
    ),
    "why" => array("Statistical inference asks how surprising one observed statistic would be under repeated random sampling. Without the sampling-distribution idea, standard errors, margins of error, and significance have no foundation.", "This lesson also changes how students interpret estimates: disagreement between samples is normal, and quality depends on both selection bias and expected variability."),
